<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-4129172">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Wed, 11/06/2013 - 21:00 | <a href="/news/2013-11-06/why-bitcoin-surging#comment-4129172" class="active">4129172</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/seek" title="View user profile.">seek</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/seek" title="View user profile."><img src="/sites/all/themes/newsflash/images/bagicon.png" alt="seek&#039;s picture" title="seek&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>My mining equipment (which is 65nm ASICs, not the most efficient) sucks 3.6 KW and with the latest difficulty adjustment, produces ~0.5 bitcoins a day now. That's 86 KWh a day (24 * 3.6) or about $13 in electricity. If all miners were at the same efficiency, 4150 bitcoins would need 713,800 KWh -- so 714 MWh to be produced. That's a fraction of the 58,352 you're showing.</p>
<p>My guess is their calculator is using power estimates from old GPU mining rigs.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

